>>
>>How'd *you* like to be the NSA guy that had broken factoring?
>>That'd have to be a rather strange position to be in: a big star in
>>a miniscule universe.
>>You'd have to sit by quietly every year Nobels were handed out.
>>Every numbers conference would find you on pins and needles-- has
>>someone else found the magic solution, and will he/she get all the
>>glory? Might you be negotiating with your employers, so that
>>evidence of your discovery would be released when and if the public
>>sector found out? I guess NSA would have to agree to terms like
>>that, or they might have difficulty getting the most precocious
>>minds...
>
>Though it's nowhere near a Nobel in the scientific community, they have a
>medal that's given out sparingly by the President. William Friedman got one.
>
>I'm not sure if it's now given publicly without specification or is still
>secret. There used to be a half-joke about visiting one's medals in a secure
>facility.
>
>In the U.K. they handle this issue rather better--there are many knighthoods
>given out for "services to industry" etc.
>
>Mostly, though, people who go to work for the NSA have rather different
>motives than notoriety, I'd think.

Like - "I gotcha, and you don't even _know_ it yet!"

